<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-248-385  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 248 385.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Jan 2 1989 n229 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microwave backbone supports statewide research; net provides data,video link for North Carolina educational institutions.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Semilof, Margie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A microwave backbone network transmits data and video for NorthCarolina educational institutions.andP;  The institutions, such as theMicroelectronics Center, an independent non-profit corporation,chose the microwave radio equipment because microwave is cheaperthan optical fiber for transmitting two-way video.andP;  Optical fiberis more expensive for video transmission because the video signalsmust be digitized.andP;  The microwave network extends 300 miles andprovides two duplex analog channels, which are shared by thecolleges and universities for transmitting and receivingmicroelectronics courses.andP;  The network uses DM2-16-25 digitalmicrowave radios from Harris Corp's Farinon Div.andP;  The video istransmitted via narrowband FM in the 6-GHz operational-fixedservice band, and the data is sent via 2-GHz operational fixedservice frequencies with 10-MHz of bandwidth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Microwave CommunicationsBackbone NetworksColleges and UniversitiesMicroelectronics Center of North CarolinaData CommunicationsVideo SystemsNorth CarolinaEducation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>